					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Jdurg wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">TPS2022 [...] Active Low Enable.<br /></div>This IC appears to basically be a pMOSFET and a current sense resistor in one package. So, yeah, you'll have the same problem as &quot;ordinary&quot; pMOSFET-based design.<br /><br />(In fact, if you're not planning on using the overcurrent pin, you might just look for a power pMOSFET instead, e.g. DMP3099)<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I also want to make sure I don't accidentally feed 1.0 amps of current to my SNES via the +5V line and fry the console.  <br /></div>Both power supplies are floating, so it's really unlikely that you could damage things in that way ... but if you want to be careful/paranoid, you could use an BJT-output optoisolator (4N26, e.g.) in lieu of a plain pulldown BJT in the schematics on the Hackaday article.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Sorry if I'm being dense or asking stupid questions, but I'm still learning here.  Heh.    <img src="./images/smilies/icon_biggrin.gif" alt=":D" title="Very Happy" /><br /></div>The only stupid thing is persisting in ignorance <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /></div>

